  "story": {
    "enabled": true,
    "heading": "The Story",
    "paragraphs": [
      "Andrew Hozier-Byrne, born near Bray, County Wicklow in 1990, broke through in 2013 with 'Take Me to Church' — a slow-building gospel-blues single that reached No. 2 on the Billboard Hot 100 for three consecutive weeks and earned a Grammy nomination for Song of the Year. His self-titled debut album followed in 2014.",
      "Wasteland, Baby! (2019) and Unreal Unearth (2023) deepened both the sound and the ambition: Unreal Unearth is structured around Dante's Inferno, its songs mapped loosely onto the nine circles of Hell as a way of working through pandemic-era isolation.",
      "In 2024, 'Too Sweet' reached No. 1 on the Billboard Hot 100 — Hozier's first US chart-topper, surpassing even 'Take Me to Church''s peak a decade earlier, and making him the first Irish act to top the Hot 100 since Sinéad O'Connor in 1990.",
      "A decade in, Hozier remains one of the few artists moving comfortably between hushed, literary songwriting and genuine mainstream chart dominance — often in the same album."
    ]
  },
